"n. 懦夫 【英】 n. 懦夫(a spiritless coward: craven) 【记】 poltr(=colt小马)+oo n→原指小马受惊→懦夫 n. 懦夫 = coward 【记】原指: 幼小的马－懦夫(polt = colt小马驹)polt = plot阴谋, roon = room: 在屋子里密谋杀害大英雄是懦夫干的事. 【记】音：怕蠢，又怕又蠢；音：怕怵，又怕又怵→懦夫 poltroon (n.)  ""A coward; a nidgit; a scoundrel"" [Johnson, who spells it poltron], 1520s, from Middle French poultron ""rascal, coward"" (16c., Modern French poltron), from Italian poltrone ""lazy fellow, coward,"" apparently from *poltro ""couch, bed"" (compare Milanese polter, Venetian poltrona ""couch""), perhaps from a Germanic source (compare Old High German polstar ""pillow;"" see bolster (n.)). Also see -oon."
